01:22
I am on episode three and, I can see why you'd say 'it's just silly' but I imagine that's the point. To establish to the viewer how silly psychosis can make an individual appear.
01:23
Psychosis doesn't make sense. It's like being in this masquerade of constant mind-fuckery, and I feel that may be the point.
01:25
We as the viewer become the individual experiencing her symptoms, and the protagonist becomes the only sensical person. To her, everything is as it is. What she believes to be true is reality, whereas to us, nothing makes sense.
01:26
It's a great technique to depict mental illness, to have the roles be reversed so that we then end up questioning, what is reality? What extent of nonsensical happenings are our brains capable of?
01:27
